SOLID PRINCIPLES:
SOLID Principles are five object-oriented design principles used in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) to write code that is clean, maintainable, reusable, and scalable.
S---->single responsibility priciple(SRP)
O---->open/closed principle(OSP)
L---->Liskov subsitution principle(LSP)
I---->interface segregation principle(ISP)
D---->dependency inversion principle(DIP)


now we have to see one by one:

SRP:Each class should perform only specific task.if a class has multiple responsibilities,it becomes different to maintain,test,modify.
     *only one responsibility and only one reason to change

OCP:Make big componets from lots of smaller ones,using props and special characters like props.children
      *the classes,modules,functions are opened for extension ,but closed for the modification 

LSP:Objects of a superclass should be replaceable with objects of its subclasses without affecting the correctness of the program.
      *If class B inherits from class A, then an object of B should be usable wherever an object of A is expected, without breaking the program.

ISP:Clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they do not use
     *Interface Segregation Principle states that a class should not be forced to implement methods that it does not need.

DIP:High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions (interfaces).
     *Dependency Inversion Principle states that high-level modules should depend on abstractions (interfaces), not on concrete classes.
